Stephen Waldis - Wikipedia





















 






Stephen Waldis

From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia


					Jump to:					navigation, 					search

Stephen Waldis is the founder and chief executive officer of Synchronoss Technologies. He and a business partner launched Synchronoss as a spinoff company of Vertek, where he worked until 2000.[1] Waldis served as president and CEO of Synchronoss until 2017, when the company acquired Intralinks and he moved into the role of Executive Chairman.[2] He resumed the role of chief executive officer in April 2017.


Stephen Waldis


Born
1968 [3]


Alma mater
Seton Hall University


Occupation
Founder and Executive Chairman of Synchronoss Technologies





Contents


1 Early Life and Education
2 Career

2.1 Founding Synchronoss
2.2 Community Involvement


3 Awards and Accolades
4 Personal life
5 References



Early Life and Education[edit]
Waldis was born in Tokyo, Japan in 1968 to an Air Force family. The family moved to New Jersey prior to Waldis beginning his early education.[4] Waldis graduated from Seton Hall University with a degree in corporate communication[4] in 1989. He walked on to the Seton Hall baseball team and later earned a scholarship to play baseball. He was a late-inning pitcher who played from 1987-1989 and was also a part of the Seton Hall 1987 Big East Tournament Championship team.[5][6]
Career[edit]
After graduating from Seton Hall, Waldis began his career at AT&T, working in technical and product management roles. In 1992,[1] he became vice president of sales & marketing at Logical Design Solutions. He later joined Vertek as chief operating officer and partner. The founder of Vertek, Jim McCormick, and Waldis set out to rebuild the company, each investing $5,000 into the business. Waldis spent 5 years with Vertek where he grew sales from $2 million to more than $32 million. Waldis and his business partners later created a spinoff business from Vertek, Synchronoss Technologies (SNCR).[4][6][5]
Founding Synchronoss[edit]
Waldis and business partner David Berry launched Synchronoss in 2000.[7][4] Waldis became chairman, president and CEO.[6][4][5] The company had only seven employees at the start, and saw a lower than expected IPO due to the deflation of the tech bubble.[4] As of 2007, the company employed over 250 people, and Waldis earned $1.3 million that year.[4] The business gained significant notability when it began handling iPhone transactions for Cingular Wireless.[8]
In 2016, Synchronoss announced it would be buying Intralinks, a cloud company. As part of the deal, Intralinks CEO Ron Hovsepian became CEO of Synchronoss and Waldis would take on the role of executive chairman.[9][2] In April 2017, Waldis resumed the role of CEO of Synchronoss.
Community Involvement[edit]
In 2011, Waldis created a summer internship program at Seton Hall University. The START (Synchronoss Technologies Academic & Recruiting Training) program has been open to students pursuing a career in computer science, engineering and software.[10]
Awards and Accolades[edit]
In 2004, Waldis received his first Ernst & Young Entrepreneur Of The Year Award.[11] He later won the award again in 2006 for the New Jersey program.[12][1] In 2006, Waldis was the founding inductee to Seton Hall’s Entrepreneur Hall of Fame.[13][14] He's also on the Center for Entrepreneurial Studies advisory board at Seton Hall.[15]
He has also sat on the board of directors at ClickFox, Inc., Factor Systems, Inc., Billtrust,[16] and New Jersey Technology Council.[17][18] Waldis is a member of the board of regents at Seton Hall.[19][20] He has also been a board director at Edison Partners.[21]
Personal life[edit]
Waldis and wife, Stacey,[4] met at Seton Hall where they both attended college. They have a son, Hunter, who signed an acceptance letter in 2016 to attend Seton Hall play baseball.[22]
